<TEXT>
newly born hurricane gustav spun toward the 
northeastern caribbean with 80 mph winds sunday tailed by tropical 
storm hortense in the midatlantic about a thousand miles to the 
east 
the governments of guadeloupe antigua barbuda montserrat 
nevis and st kitts issued hurricane warnings sunday according to 
the national hurricane center in suburban coral gables 
a hurricane watch remained in effect for dominica martinique 
st martin anguilla and surrounding islands said bob sheets 
director of the center 
at 1030 pm edt gustav which reached hurricane strength 
earlier in the day was centered near 157 degrees north latitude 
572 degrees west longitude or about 280 miles eastsoutheast of 
guadeloupe it was moving northwest near 9 mph and was expected to 
maintain that course and speed through noon monday 
maximum sustained winds were near 80 mph and some increase in 
strength was likely during the forecast period the center said 
meanwhile hortense the eighth named storm of the atlantic 
season had gathered top sustained winds of 45 mph and was growing 
stronger its course turning to the north 
at 1030 pm edt hortense was centered near 176 degrees north 
latitude 405 degrees west longitude or about 990 miles west of 
the westernmost cape verde islands it was moving north near 5 mph 
on a course expected to hold through monday morning 
forecaster bob case said the storms were far enough apart not to 
affect each other 
were not seeing interaction between the storms he said 
both storms were born as tropical depressions off the cape verde 
islands on the western tip of africa such storms typical for this 
the busiest time of the atlantic season have been among historys 
worst forecasters note 
case said a tropical wave potential forerunner to a depression 
was shaping up over western africa but wasnt of much concern at 
the moment because of gustav and hortense 
theyre keeping us quite busy he said the two of them 
are plenty 
tropical depressions become named storms when their top 
sustained winds top 39 mph they become hurricanes if those winds 
hit 74 mph 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

