more than a million israeli schoolchildren will 
get an intensive course in the use of gas masks and other ways of 
surviving chemical warfare to prepare for a possible iraqi attack 
officials said sunday 
the program to begin when school starts sept 2 follows 
threats earlier this year by iraqi president saddam hussein to 
attack israel with chemical weapons if an israeli nuclear attack is 
aimed at iraq 
the children will be instructed how to put on their gas masks 
and walk up to the upper floors of the school to previously sealed 
off classrooms ran levine deputy director general of the 
education ministry told israel radio 
according to officials the instruction will be given to all 
israeli students both jews and arabs between age 5 and 18 
some 5000 teachers will take a course on using the protective 
equipment two teachers from each school will then complete 
instruction for the students by sept 20 each school will receive 
a videotape and 25 gas masks for demonstrations officials said 
dr avigdor klingman the education ministrys coordinator for 
crisis intervention said the course also is designed to quiet 
childrens fears about gas masks 
a child who thinks that he cant wear a mask because it is too 
scary then puts it on with the help of his teacher paints with 
it or does exercises with it then sees that the devil is not so 
bad klingman said 
gas masks will not be handed out at schools but will be 
distributed to families through neighborhood civil defense offices 
despite the recent crisis israeli authorities have decided not 
to distribute the masks to the public now for fear of causing panic 
or sending a wrong signal to iraq 
saddam first warned he would use chemical weapons against israel 
last april during the current crisis he has threatened to attack 
israel in response to a us military strike but he has not 
specifically mentioned chemical weapons 
bomb drills have always been part of israels school curriculum 
in the past four years instruction on protection against 
chemical warfare has been introduced at some 250 middle and high 
schools this year the program is being expanded to all schools 
 
