<TEXT>
angolan writer and politician mario 
pinto de andrade a pioneer in angolas struggle against portuguese 
colonial rule died sunday in london after a long illness he was 
62 
although he dropped out of angolan politics in the mid1970s 
pinto de andrade remained an influential figure in the wartorn 
southern african country 
pinto de andrade became the first president of the popular 
movement for the liberation of angola in 1960 just before the 
marxist group launched its 15year guerrilla war to end portuguese 
colonial rule 
in 1974 he split with the popular movement which came to power 
the following year when angola became independent 
since 1975 pinto de andrade lived mainly in guineabissau both 
the popular movement government and the usbacked unita rebels 
tried unsuccessfully to win his support in the continuing civil war 
that followed angolan independence 
recently he worked with other popular movement veterans in an 
effort to mediate the conflict his brother joaquim pinto de 
andrade leads an independent human rights group in angola 
the nationalists death came as delegations from the government 
and unita the national union for the total independence of angola 
arrived in lisbon for talks aimed at reaching a ceasefire in the 
15yearold civil war 
pinto de andrade was born in 1928 in the northern angolan town 
of golungo alto and attended high school in the capital luanda he 
studied classical philosophy at lisbon university 
in lisbon in the 1950s he worked with other african 
nationalists from portuguesespeaking africa including the poet 
agostinho neto who became angolas first president and amilcar 
cabral who led guineabissaus struggle for independence in the 
1960s 
they tried to promote african culture and nationalist ideas in 
portugals five african colonies angola mozambique 
guineabissau cape verde and sao tome e principe 
pinto de andrade edited an anthology of portuguese african 
poetry that was published in 1969 which helped widen international 
awareness of the culture and provided a focus for young african 
intellectuals 
after he split with the popular movement and left angola in 
1974 pinto de andrade worked for the government of 
newlyindependent guineabissau as general secretary of the 
national cultural council 
in 1980 he was appointed guineabissaus representative on the 
executive council of unesco 
his last book a history of the nationalist movements in 
portuguesespeaking africa is due to be published soon 
there was no immediate information on his survivors or funeral 
arrangements 
