<TEXT>
junk bond defaults rose in the first half of 
1990 and analysts say a weak economy and higher oil prices could 
bring the highest default rate in 20 years 
as the economy slows and higher gasoline and heating oil prices 
leave consumers with less money to spend in casinos department 
stores and on new homes businesses will have less cash to make 
interest and principal payments 
in the first seven months of the year 32 highyield bond 
issuers defaulted for an annualized rate of 58 percent according 
to john lonski chief economists at moodys investor service inc 
if maintained the it would be the highest rate since the 
collapse of the penn central railroad accounted for a 109 percent 
default rate in 1970 lonski said 
i dont think weve passed the bottom yet in all likelihood 
especially for the highlyleveraged firms that depend on 
descretionary income lonski said 
prices of issues expected to ride up and down with the business 
cycle have taken a pounding since oil prices rose after iraq 
overran kuwait on aug 2 
numbers compiled by citicorp show total returns on junk bonds 
issued by recessionprone industries suffered the worst in the 
first half of august casinos dropped 78 percent building 
materials fell 71 percent and retailers are off 36 percent 
toilet maker american standard inc which relies heavily on 
energy in making ceramics as well as new homes for sales saw its 
12percent senior subordinated debentures that mature in the year 
2000 skid from 93 to the high 80s last week 
junk bonds are debt securities typically issued by companies 
that lack investment grade credit often used to raise capital for 
expansion they carry high interest rates to compensate for their 
risky nature 
the market is reflecting fears of a recession it was already 
worried about corporate profits weakening said mariel clemensen 
citicorps highyield research director 
a recession would hit steeply leveraged companies particularly 
hard which have huge principal and interest payments among their 
fixed costs lonski said when looking to cut expenses capital 
spending and employment are likely to be hit harder than if a 
company didnt have a high debt obligation 
even industries such as food tobacco and health care whose 
fortunes tend to resist economic downturns could be hurt as 
consumers resist price hikes that heavily indebted companies have 
relied upon to boost cash flow lonski said 
citicorps numbers show total returns on healthcare issues 
dropping 09 percent and broadcasting issues falling 17 percent in 
the first half of august 
you might find some that will escape unscathed lonski said 
particularly utilities that rely heavily on nuclear power to 
produce electricity 
for utilities junk bonds are usually socalled fallen angels 
once highly rated issues that became viewed as risky the more they 
faced trouble with their investments in nuclear power 
but these utilities reliance on nuclear power is what may make 
some an attractive investment during a prolonged oilprice shock 
lonski said arizona public service co and philadelphia electric 
co for example are two utilities with speculativegrade bonds 
that have substantial nuclearpower generating capabilities 
moreover public sentiment about nuclear power could improve if 
the country once again starts looking to alternative fuel sources 
